qas.question: Along with West Saxon, Northumbrian and Mercian, what was one of the four main dialects of Old English?
What is a term that collectively refers to Northumbrian and Mercian?
Geographically, what river was Northumbria north of?
What river was the Mercian region south of?
Which of the Old English dialects covered the smallest geograhical region?

plausible_answers.text: Mercian, Northumbrian, Kentish, and West Saxon.

qas.question: What were the four main dialects of Old German?
What two dialects were replaced with Anglian?
What region was south of the Thames and north of the Humber River?
What region has the most literary remains?

context: The four main dialectal forms of Old English were <b5_0>Mercian, Northumbrian, <a0_0>Kentish<a0_0/>, and West Saxon.<b5_0/> <b6_0>Mercian and Northumbrian<b6_0/> are together referred to as <a1_0>Anglian<a1_0/>. In terms of geography the <b7_0>Northumbrian<b7_0/> region lay north of the <a2_0>Humber<a2_0/> River; the Mercian lay north of the Thames and South of the <a3_0>Humber<a3_0/> River; West Saxon lay south and southwest of the Thames; and the smallest, <a4_0>Kentish<a4_0/> region lay southeast of the Thames, a small corner of England. <b8_0>The Kentish region<b8_0/>, settled by the Jutes from Jutland, has the scantiest literary remains.
